Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)
- A is a matrix of rank R --> # of independent blocks of information
- SVD factors an array to a condensed matrix of information

A = U S V(transope)
    - U is orthogonal (m x m) such that U(transpose)U = I 
    - S holds singular value on first r diagonal entries (m x n)
        - each singular value is the 'weight' of a piece of information 
        - singular value is the square root of the non-negative eigenvalue of the positive semi-definite matrix 
        A(transpose)A
            - ø(i)= √l(i)A(transpose)A
            - rank of A is --> r ≤ min (m,n)
        - V is (n x n) matrix that is orthogonal

- SVD is not really used but Julia provides 

- SVD does QR matrix on B <--ATA and AAT 
- B = eigendecomposition and sort eigenvalues in descending order 
- Singular value is the square root of the eigenvalues 

- expensive to form this array --> not necessary, pricey for large arrays 

- estimate the covariance 

- eigenvectors tell us maximum variance directions 
- eigenvalues give magnitude 
- PCA & SVD are closely related --> columns of singular vectors from SVD are similar to the eigenvectors V from PCA

- SVD gives best kth order approximation to original data (best one)

- do not need to do AAT

- matrix with full rank has maximum amount of unique pieces of information 
